<br>
Okay, for one reason or another, you want to type in Japanese, whether it's for posting online, printing to hand in for a class, or just for a bit of fun. It's fairly easy to set up, but a little confusing at first, so I will walk you through it.<br>
<br>
The first step is to go to to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> Start &gt; Settings &gt; Control Panel</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. Once you're there, click on Regional Options (may also be called &quot;Regional Settings&quot;).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.spikescafe.com/crit/IMEsetup/1.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Once you're in the menu, click on the furthest tab to the right, labeled as &quot;Input Locales&quot;. Your screen should be similar to this:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.spikescafe.com/crit/IMEsetup/2.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
From here, click on &quot;Add&quot;, and specify Japanese as follows:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.spikescafe.com/crit/IMEsetup/3.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
After you click OK, you may be prompted to insert your Windows disk after selecting this option; if this is the case, let Windows guide you though the process.  You're almost done, now, just make sure that &quot;Enable indicator on taskbar&quot; is selected.  Click on &quot;Apply&quot;, and look at the bottom right corner of your taskbar to see if there is a blue icon:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.spikescafe.com/crit/IMEsetup/4.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
You can click on this, but it won't always allow you to do anything. You'll have to have some kind of text editor open which can use multiple fonts, such as WordPad or Microsoft Word. Also, if your web browser has Japanese display capabilities*, you can type right into a text message on ezboard!<br>
<br>
Once you have one of these programs open, click on the blue icon and select your Japanese IME:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.spikescafe.com/crit/IMEsetup/5.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Now, you'll see a small toolbar on the top of your screen. The first box is the most important, and allows you to change between Hiragana, Katakana, and Direct Input (Romanji). To type in Japanese, just spell out the words as if they were written in English, and the IME will translate them as you go.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.spikescafe.com/crit/IMEsetup/6.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
You can find more about typing by right-clicking on the toolbar and going to their help topics. Type a character twice to get a small tsu before it. <br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Ex: issho =</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> いっしょ<br>
<br>
Also, play around with the spacebar and Enter key to find out exactly how they work and when they should be pressed. Don't let the IME convert to kanji words you don't know, or it will be very confusing to read what you have to say! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Hopefully this tutorial was helpful to everyone!<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
