-maimai<br>
------<br>
<br>
I was chatting with one of my friends the other day, trying to convince her to buy me one of the super cool Tablet PCs I saw in Yodabashi Camera when I was in Japan last.  When pressed why on earth I would ever desire such a thing (why she can't understand that &quot;tablet&quot; + &quot;computer&quot; = &quot;object of desire&quot; is beyond me *grin* )  I replied that beyond the obvious cool factor, there is the added benefit of being able to directly input japanese into my computer simply by writing.  (My electronic dictionary (a sharp) has that ability, and I find it so incredibly helpful...).<br>
<br>
Needless to say, I failed to convince her to buy me a tablet PC *sigh*.  But it got me thinking - there *must* be a way to rig up my current computer to do allow direct japanese input.  After a little bit of fiddling, i figured out how.  Now, I'm a rather slow panda, so if any of you have already figured this out, my apologies.  <br>
<br>
In case you're wondering why on earth you would want the ability to write kanji directly into your computer, think about how many times you have seen a kanji (in a book, compound etc) that you would like to type (in a letter, or put into a translator etc) on your computer. ... however, if you're in this forum, chances are your kanji, like mine, still have a long way to go until you're fluent.  So you do the only thing available to you: you start flipping through your dictionary, looking up radicals, etc. until you finally track down the character you're looking for 3 days later and then finding the various readings, manage to input it into the computer.  Even if you have an electronic dictionary, it is still annoying to have to use two machines to accomplish one simple task, especially since the computer knows infinetly more kanji than all of us combined.<br>
<br>
--- <br>
START OF TUTORIAL<br>
---<br>
to start, you will need to be running Windows XP, with japanese language support enabled.  If you don't know how to do this, refer to the sticky post at the top of the japanese language forum.  <br>
--<br>
You will need the language bar floating on your screen.  (there's no real reason why you need the language bar, but it's infinitely more convinient than always messing around with the icon in the lower right - plus you can turn it transparent and then it really looks cool).  To enable the language bar, click on the JP language icon in the lower left hand corner like so:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/language/2languagebar.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
A: The Japanese/English/Etc. language setting icon<br>
<br>
B: &quot;Restore...&quot; to restore the language bar to its floating status<br>
--<br>
Now you will need click on the IME PAD button on the language bar and select the direct input option (tegaki - &quot;hand write&quot;) indicated by the arrow below:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/language/1tegaki.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
--<br>
Now you will get the direct input IME pad floating on your screen. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/language/3IMEpad.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
A. This is where you will write the character directly using your mouse (or tablet - more about that below). <br>
B. As you write, you will be able to select from the characters that the computer thinks matches what you're writing.<br>
C. &quot;modosu&quot; - this is like an &quot;undo&quot; key that will undo one stroke at a time, useful for when you screw up a stroke order accidentally.<br>
D. &quot;kesu&quot; - this clears your screen, so if you want to write a completely new character, etc.<br>
--<br>
Below, you can see I've started to write the character for &quot;katayoru&quot; - &quot;to be biased/lean&quot;.  The actual character I want is indicated by an arrow.  However, I haven't finished writing the character, so there's a few other options how it could turn out (which is why there's still a couple other characters ahead of it).  You can click on the character whenever you want (you don't have to finish writing the character on the left) but i recommend always finishing your character so you don't become lazy and end up like some modern japanese children, unable to write kanji without the aid of a computer, or at least a ketai (cell phone - I had a japanese friend who actually used her cell phone to check how to write kanji more than she actually talked on it).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/language/4.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
--<br>
Here you can see that I've finished writing the character (A) and that the character for &quot;katayoru&quot; has moved into the first place on the right (B) [IGNORE the fact that the arrow actually points to the wrong character - I made a mistake.  &quot;Katayoru&quot; is actually the character to the left of the arrow.  SORRY! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   ]<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/language/5.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
--<br>
Now you simply click on the appropriate character (A), and it goes into the &quot;queue&quot; (B) of characters waiting to be written  (this will make more sense if you routinely work with the Japanese input system - in this case I don't have an application like word, etc. into which to input the character, which is why it's floating around).<br>
<br>
You will notice that as an added benefit, resting your mouse on top of the character will bring up a floating box which will tell you the onyomi (&quot;hen&quot; in this case) (if you don't know which is which, the onyomi is always written in katakana) and the kunyomi (katayo-ru) (written in hiragana, and the characters after the dot indicate the furigana for the character - that is to say, the part of the word that is NOT replaced by the kanji).  This is great if you're just looking for a pronunciation, etc.  Not so good if you don't know the meaning <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/language/6.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
